WEBVTT

00:08.860 --> 00:12.800
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.500 --> 00:33.760
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.460 --> 00:38.060
And here are your hosts.

00:42.080 --> 00:44.060
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson.

00:44.620 --> 00:47.560
Ray Bradbury has tried just about every form of writing an author can undertake.

00:48.060 --> 00:50.620
Short stories, novels, poetry plays, even an opera.

00:51.000 --> 00:53.160
And he's also written numerous television and movie scripts.

00:53.440 --> 00:56.500
He used to write shows back in the 60s for Twilight Zone and offered Hitchcock.

01:12.420 --> 01:16.820
We asked Bradbury if he still does television scripts, particularly the kind that are written

01:16.820 --> 01:17.820
on cue with the deadline.

01:18.820 --> 01:21.160
Well, I tried never to do that anyway.

01:21.600 --> 01:29.520
I had a very friendly relationship with Alfred Hitchcock and all of his partners, Daryl

01:29.520 --> 01:31.560
Jones Harrison and Norman Lloyd.

01:31.700 --> 01:35.020
I'd go out and have a casual lunch, tell them an idea.

01:35.680 --> 01:36.720
They'd okay it.

01:36.740 --> 01:41.680
I'd go home and write it and come back with a finished script and we'd have another lunch.

01:42.040 --> 01:45.240
If they could argue me into any changes, I'd make them.

01:45.240 --> 01:49.880
And if I could argue them into the logic of my situation, it stayed the way it was.

01:50.120 --> 01:52.960
So it was a very amiable, very friendly thing.

01:53.320 --> 01:55.140
I never did a lot of scripts.

01:55.800 --> 02:01.880
I wouldn't let myself get bullied into being a full-time writer because no one remembers

02:01.880 --> 02:04.060
who writes scripts for television anyway.

02:05.220 --> 02:07.320
Bradbury still writes for television occasionally.

02:07.820 --> 02:11.800
Last year he had two shows that were successful, The Electric Grandmother and Any Friend of

02:11.800 --> 02:13.360
Nicholas Nicolby is a friend of mine.

02:13.900 --> 02:16.160
That last work is based on a play Bradbury had written.

02:16.500 --> 02:18.240
We asked him how many of his plays had been produced.

02:19.340 --> 02:25.180
Oh, I would say somewhere around 14 or 15 of them.

02:25.260 --> 02:26.960
Most of them I produced myself.

02:27.980 --> 02:32.380
Dan Limewine here on the coast recently, back east a few years ago.

02:33.140 --> 02:36.440
The Martian Chronicles which I produced here at a small theater.

02:37.840 --> 02:41.480
Fahrenheit 451, two years ago which turned out very well.

02:41.960 --> 02:46.360
The wonderful ice cream suit and six or seven of my one-act plays.

02:47.100 --> 02:52.260
I've had the Anthem Sprinters which is all of my Irish experiences.

02:53.300 --> 02:58.180
So I've had a lot of fun with it and I've made a lot of friends among actors.

02:58.680 --> 03:03.700
I've worked with a lot of good people including James Whitmore who appeared in my first one-act

03:03.700 --> 03:09.120
play here and had a benefit for the United Nations about 23 years ago.

03:09.940 --> 03:12.920
It's obvious from all of Bradbury's fiction that he is a lover of books.

03:13.300 --> 03:15.380
Fahrenheit 451 is a good example of that.

03:15.780 --> 03:20.080
We wondered then how he could devote so much energy to the visual arts like television or the movies.

03:21.220 --> 03:23.320
I grew up with all these loves.

03:23.480 --> 03:28.340
If I have any capacity at all it's to be in love in six or seven different ways.

03:28.520 --> 03:31.580
So I've always been madly in love with motion pictures.

03:31.900 --> 03:36.900
My mother was a fiend for them and took me to see hundreds of films.

03:37.480 --> 03:43.300
From the age of when I was two until up until I was 10, 11 or 12.

03:43.620 --> 03:49.780
So that never left me and I think I'm very fortunate to have a great love of films,

03:49.920 --> 03:55.420
a great love of libraries and books, a great love of radio and the famous people in radio.

03:55.700 --> 04:02.880
When I came west to live in Los Angeles I headed downtown immediately and got to know all the people

04:02.880 --> 04:09.940
on an old radio broadcast called Hollywood Hotel and Laurel Parsons became a friend to this

04:10.640 --> 04:19.580
13, 14 year old boy and I knew Burns and Allen during those years of 1934, 35, 36.

04:20.120 --> 04:23.500
I wrote scripts for them every week and handed them in.

04:23.680 --> 04:31.540
Of course I doubt if they even read them but they pretended that they did and they were very kind to me.

04:31.540 --> 04:37.920
And then I was in love with Orson Welles when he came on the scene in radio and suspense

04:38.560 --> 04:43.360
and Norman Corwin who became my friend when I was 27 years old.

04:43.760 --> 04:51.200
So I grew up then with a love of libraries, a love of radio, a love of films and I think I'm very lucky

04:51.200 --> 04:57.340
that I've been able to work in all of these different mediums and do rather well in each one of them.

04:58.260 --> 04:59.660
More next time with Ray Bradbury.

