06:24.000 --> 06:29.340
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:31.980 --> 06:33.660
And here are your hosts.

06:37.780 --> 06:42.440
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Ray Bradbury, who most readers recognize as a

06:42.440 --> 06:47.020
Science Fiction author, has been writing poetry for most of his life. And he publishes it regularly too

06:47.020 --> 06:51.100
in all sorts of magazines every so often the poems are collected together in a single volume.

06:51.560 --> 06:55.780
There have been four of these collections so far. When elephants last in the doryard bloomed,

06:56.180 --> 07:01.280
where robot mice and robot men run around in robot towns, the haunted computer and the android pope,

07:01.280 --> 07:03.800
and most recently the complete poems of Ray Bradbury.

07:18.360 --> 07:22.220
We asked Bradbury when he sits down to write what determines what will come out,

07:22.420 --> 07:25.360
a story, a novel, a play, an opera, whatever.

07:31.280 --> 07:37.160
When I'm writing a poem, I'll say, oh my, this is too big for a poem. I may very well finish the poem,

07:37.220 --> 07:43.820
but then I sit down and turn it into a short story immediately, or on a rare occasion it turns into a

07:44.420 --> 07:50.140
stage play or a novel. But that doesn't happen as often. Most of the time I work in the short form.

07:51.640 --> 07:59.500
But quite often you take the simplest idea and it evolves from the poetry form

08:00.060 --> 08:06.860
into, well, I was, for instance, I was driving around in England a few years ago,

08:07.100 --> 08:15.720
and a chauffeur of our car was talking about driving in the Irish and funerals, the Irish wakes and what

08:15.720 --> 08:21.500
have you, and he told of this one wake of some friends of his in a small town in Ireland,

08:22.220 --> 08:28.620
where an English lord lived nearby. When he died, he went against the old saying,

08:28.620 --> 08:35.440
you can't take it with you, and he took with him all of his wine, and he had all the thousands of

08:35.440 --> 08:42.760
bottles of wine in his cellar poured into his grave. Well, it was such a great idea that I

08:42.760 --> 08:48.680
wrote it as a short story last week and sent it off, and it'll probably be in playboy sometime in

08:48.680 --> 08:53.940
the next three or four, five months. We asked Bradbury if he could name one or two of his favorite

08:53.940 --> 08:59.080
poems from his own work. At the time I write them, of course, I think each one is good,

08:59.120 --> 09:04.640
or I wouldn't have put it in the book. I try not to ever publish a poem or a short story that I've

09:05.580 --> 09:13.340
gotten tired of. With his incredibly busy schedule, will he continue to write poetry? Oh, yes, yes, yes.

09:21.760 --> 09:25.260
Those science fiction fans who might have been surprised that Bradbury writes poetry have

09:25.260 --> 09:28.900
another surprise ahead of them. When we asked Bradbury if there was a form of writing he hadn't

09:28.900 --> 09:35.960
tried yet, his answer contained a mild shocker. I can't think of anything offhand. Now that I'm

09:35.960 --> 09:43.080
working on this libretto for this opera, that sort of rounds out the list, I would, I'm working on

09:43.080 --> 09:49.060
a detective murder mystery novel now, which I've never done before, so it's a new, it's a change for

09:49.060 --> 09:55.680
me in the novel form. I've been a great lover and admirer of Dashiell Hammett and Raymond Chandler

09:55.680 --> 10:02.680
for the last 40 years or so, and I always wanted to do something in that field, but I was afraid to

10:02.680 --> 10:08.860
do it because I wasn't well enough educated, even though I'd read hundreds of novels in the field

10:08.860 --> 10:14.060
when I was younger. It didn't seem to get into my bloodstream, but now I think I'm old enough,

10:14.600 --> 10:20.820
and I hope I've learned my lessons, and when the novel comes out people will agree that it's at least

10:20.820 --> 10:25.760
an agreeable competitor in the field. Could he tell us when the novel might be published?

10:26.500 --> 10:32.460
No, I would say about a year from now. It's right up close to being finished. I've been working on

10:32.460 --> 10:39.320
seven or eight years, but you never know. I might finish it all in one week in the next week or two,

10:39.480 --> 10:45.640
and again, I may drag on for another six months. I'm not in charge. I don't make the decisions.

10:46.920 --> 10:48.840
We'll have more next time with Ray Bradbury.

