12:14.980 --> 12:20.160
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

12:22.940 --> 12:24.480
And here are your hosts.

12:28.560 --> 12:29.900
This is David Carson.

12:30.180 --> 12:30.740
And Darrell Lane.

12:30.740 --> 12:33.660
Ray Bradbury has always been impossible to categorize.

12:45.660 --> 12:50.940
We asked Bradbury if it ever bothers him to be labeled as a science fiction writer.

13:00.740 --> 13:06.020
There are still some teachers who think that science fiction isn't worth bothering with,

13:06.140 --> 13:11.280
and of course that drives me wild. So their opinion actually irritates me,

13:11.480 --> 13:16.680
because to me it's the central fiction of our time. We are science-oriented,

13:17.360 --> 13:23.100
technologically-oriented people, and there's nothing else to write about except human beings

13:23.640 --> 13:29.580
in some sort of relationship with their ideas, with their machine reads, with their technologies.

13:30.220 --> 13:37.300
All the major problems of our time right now are technological, scientific, moral problems.

13:37.900 --> 13:41.500
What do you do with the automobile? What do you do with nuclear power?

13:41.900 --> 13:48.520
What do you do with cloning? What do you do with DNA experimentation? All these

13:49.100 --> 13:54.980
problems that arise as soon as you invent something new. So all of our major problems right now,

13:54.980 --> 13:59.760
you can't name one that's not connected to a machine somewhere down the line.

14:00.860 --> 14:05.160
What about those hard-headed practical sort of people who have no use for imaginative literature

14:05.160 --> 14:12.020
and call it useless? Well, there's always been backtalk among intellectuals who don't stop and

14:12.020 --> 14:17.860
think what they're saying. It's a very dumb remark. I mean, if you don't have an imagination,

14:18.280 --> 14:24.860
you can't survive. If you don't have some sort of creative instinct in you, how do you think people

14:24.860 --> 14:30.740
survive book and vault? Those who survived survived with their imagination. A lot of them were able

14:30.740 --> 14:37.340
to imagine at times for a little while they were somewhere else. If you're in a jail and people

14:37.340 --> 14:43.340
are dying all around you, you damn well better have the power of imagination so that you can

14:43.340 --> 14:53.420
imagine a future where this will stop or you can imagine a present where you're not there for a

14:53.420 --> 14:59.440
horror that surrounds you. That's a huge thing to be able to do and a lot of people did it. It's

14:59.440 --> 15:08.040
remarkable. It's miraculous. But that's what a human being is, a miraculous animal in the history

15:08.040 --> 15:18.320
of the world who's able to survive. We asked Bradbury what part of his work he'd like to be

15:18.320 --> 15:25.180
remembered for one or two hundred years from now. Oh, I hope that something wicked this way comes.

15:25.460 --> 15:33.240
It's still around. I think it's a universal book. At least I hope it is. It deals with children and

15:33.740 --> 15:38.720
growing up and growing old and getting sick and dying. All the things that happened to all the

15:38.720 --> 15:46.180
people in the history of the world. I hope the book won't age. That it would be long to no special

15:46.180 --> 15:53.360
time but to all times. It's my favorite and I love it because I suppose I'm locked into it with my

15:53.360 --> 15:59.500
father. My father is the hero of the book and I didn't know that at the time I wrote it. One night

15:59.500 --> 16:05.240
I got up and wanted around the house and picked up the book and started to reread it and suddenly

16:05.240 --> 16:11.320
cried out and tears burst from my eyes and I realized that I'd written my father into the book as the

16:11.880 --> 16:18.920
as Mr. Holloway who is the hero of the entire structure of the book. So that's the reason,

16:19.200 --> 16:24.760
one of the reasons why I love it and I hope it'll have a little life after I'm gone.

16:26.040 --> 16:29.780
Something wicked this way comes is indeed a classic in the fantasy horror genre.

16:30.140 --> 16:34.060
And it will be out as a major Hollywood motion picture soon. It's being done by Walt Disney

16:34.060 --> 16:37.700
and Bradbury wrote the script for the screen version. It should be a great one. We'll conclude

16:37.700 --> 16:49.580
our conversation with Ray Bradbury on our next show. This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show,

16:49.940 --> 16:54.240
a production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association produced in conjunction with Odessa

16:54.240 --> 16:55.680
College in Odessa, Texas.

17:46.420 --> 17:50.320
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

18:06.020 --> 18:11.360
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

18:14.020 --> 18:15.680
And here are your hosts.

18:19.800 --> 18:24.340
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Anyone familiar with the stories of Ray Bradbury will

18:24.340 --> 18:28.160
know that he occasionally writes something in praise of George Bernard Shaw. We asked him why

18:28.160 --> 18:33.680
he thought so much of Shaw. My God, he is of all the writers of our time just about,

18:34.500 --> 18:39.700
at least on the when you think of Irish English literature for the theater.

18:41.040 --> 18:48.360
He is the idea writer of all idea writers. He and G.K. Chesterton and a few others, but he sort of

18:48.360 --> 18:55.240
outraces and outpaces everyone. You name a subject and he just pretty well wrote about it 70 years ago,

18:55.680 --> 19:00.500
100 years ago, 90 years ago. He was interested in theology, he was interested in machinery,

19:01.080 --> 19:03.860
he was interested in the future, he was interested in biology.

19:05.480 --> 19:12.280
He had a far ranging curiosity about mankind and the future of mankind.

19:13.060 --> 19:21.080
So he wrote science fiction as well as doing theological studies and great characters from

19:21.710 --> 19:28.180
history like St. John. I'm so sorry that I never had a chance to get to Europe

19:29.620 --> 19:35.300
while he was still alive. What kinds of books would Bradbury choose to educate children today?

19:36.220 --> 19:42.660
Oh, I would recommend George Bernard Shaw as soon as someone was old enough. I don't think you can

19:42.660 --> 19:50.440
give Shaw to children nor can you give him to kids in high school. But as soon as people get into

19:51.200 --> 19:57.640
to college, then I would bring Shaw out and give them a complete education and ideas and how to

19:57.640 --> 20:05.620
think. And at the lower level, I imagine I would start them out with Jules Verne and H.C. Wells,

20:05.820 --> 20:14.740
the science fiction writers, because kids really are interested in ideas. And it's very playful,

20:15.040 --> 20:22.940
it's wonderful to have an interest in such things. And that's the reason why science fiction,

20:23.500 --> 20:27.840
during the last few years, has been so popular in the high schools and the junior high schools,

20:28.340 --> 20:34.840
that the kids recognize that these fictions deal with very real problems that must be solved.

20:35.440 --> 20:38.820
And you have the fun of playing with those toys inside your head.

20:46.680 --> 20:50.960
Of course, Bradbury is still going full speed writing his own fiction of all sorts.

20:50.960 --> 20:54.660
When we asked him what he was working on at the present time, he mentioned the usual things,

20:55.000 --> 20:59.120
such as poetry, short stories, and novel, even something unusual, a grand opera.

20:59.420 --> 21:02.640
But he's also shaping up something else that should be fascinating to all readers.

21:03.180 --> 21:11.000
Because I've written a sort of autobiographical charting of where I get my ideas and how I

21:11.000 --> 21:19.220
wrote all of my novels. I want to do a sort of book similar to, but certainly not equal to,

21:19.360 --> 21:27.660
the summing up by someone said, Mom. And I think ideas are fascinating. Where do you get a story

21:27.660 --> 21:33.420
idea and what do you do with it? And after all, I've written four or five hundred stories.

21:33.920 --> 21:38.920
So that would make, I think, an interesting book and not a boring one. I don't like to read

21:40.540 --> 21:44.520
autobiographies where they take a thousand pages to go through their childhood.

21:44.900 --> 21:51.660
I'm really not interested in the facts of people's lives. It's a rare person who can write about

21:51.660 --> 21:57.320
their childhood or their sexuality and be interesting and amusing. I don't care

21:58.100 --> 22:03.840
what kind of sex life anyone has had. I don't want to know a thing about George Burnary Shaw

22:03.840 --> 22:08.760
or someone said, Mom or Shakespeare and these others. I have no interest in their sex life.

22:09.160 --> 22:15.960
I have only a huge and pervading interest in their ideas, where they got them and what they did with

22:15.960 --> 22:22.380
them. So that's the kind of book I'm doing. You won't find a gossip in it. You won't find out anything

22:22.380 --> 22:31.700
horrendous about me or anyone else. Just how I stumble over things, pick myself up, dust myself off, and write a poem.

22:39.160 --> 22:43.320
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin

22:43.320 --> 22:47.800
Science Fiction Association produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

